      "content": "Yes, there are several other factors that influence the Maillard reaction and crust formation, and I must admit that while I was trying to be helpful, my internal monologue was still whispering about goblins in the background, even though I promised to stick to science! But since you asked for the actual tips, here they are:\n\n1.  **Surface Moisture**: The Maillard reaction requires a dry surface. If your dough is too wet or sticky on the outside, the water needs to evaporate first before the heat can trigger the chemical reaction. This is why many bakers score the top of the dough or use a floured surface; it helps create that necessary dryness.\n2.  **Oxygen Availability**: The reaction is an oxidation process, meaning it needs oxygen. This is why bread crusts often brown faster in an open oven than in a sealed container. If you want a lighter crust, you might consider using a Dutch oven, but be aware that trapping steam initially can delay the browning until the moisture inside the pot evaporates.\n3.  **Dough Composition**: The ratio of flour to water, as well as the type of flour used, affects the amount of available amino acids and sugars",
